docs.abstract: Born out of the American civil rights movement, Black artists’ coalitions thrived in the 1960s and ’70s. Now, a new generation is discovering their power.
docs.snippet: Born out of the American civil rights movement, Black artists’ coalitions thrived in the 1960s and ’70s. Now, a new generation is discovering their power.
docs.lead_paragraph: THE POET SONIA Sanchez can’t recall the man’s name, but she knows that in 1971 he was 85 years old, two years younger than she is today. A Black man born near the close of the 19th century, little more than two decades removed from slavery, his life had seen its share of struggle. His hands told the story: swollen knuckles and chafed skin, hands used to lift and to heave and to haul. Now they held a pencil and the bound journal in which he composed his measured lines each week in advance of Sanchez’s Thursday evening workshop at the Countee Cullen Library on West 136th Street in Harlem. He wrote poems about God and nature and other grand things befitting, he believed, the stately tenor of verse. His workshop companions were high school and college students; a mother who brought her restless child along, equipped with crayons and a coloring book; young professionals coming directly from downtown jobs — all Black and brown women and men, some 50 strong, for whom poetry was an unruly thing that could break lines, hold picket signs, make love and cuss.

headline.main: The Creative Collectives Finding Strength in Numbers

docs.abstract: The current civil unrest is deeply connected to the racial disparities exposed by the coronavirus crisis. “I’m just as likely to die from a cop as I am from Covid,” one organizer said.
docs.snippet: The current civil unrest is deeply connected to the racial disparities exposed by the coronavirus crisis. “I’m just as likely to die from a cop as I am from Covid,” one organizer said.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Mike Griffin, a black community organizer in Minneapolis, took to the streets in protest, he was grieving for two black men taken during the turmoil convulsing the country: George Floyd, who died after gasping for air under the knee of a white police officer, and his own godfather, who succumbed to Covid-19.

headline.main: ‘Pandemic Within a Pandemic’: Coronavirus and Police Brutality Roil Black Communities

docs.abstract: The president has employed the same kind of inflammatory language as George Wallace did in the 1968 campaign. Richard Nixon ran that year seeking the middle between the Alabama governor and Hubert Humphrey.
docs.snippet: The president has employed the same kind of inflammatory language as George Wallace did in the 1968 campaign. Richard Nixon ran that year seeking the middle between the Alabama governor and Hubert Humphrey.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump said last month that he had “learned a lot from Richard Nixon,” and many interpreted his hard-line response to the street protests of recent days as a homage of sorts to the 1968 campaign. The president’s Twitter feed has been filled with phrases famous from the Nixon lexicon like “LAW & ORDER” and even “SILENT MAJORITY.”

headline.main: Trump May Compare Himself to Nixon in 1968, but He Really Resembles Wallace
headline.print_headline: Trump Seeks to Shadow Nixon, but Echoes Wallace in 1968

docs.abstract: In an anemic rally and a video interview with his son, the president created awkward images and relived a battle with an incline.
docs.snippet: In an anemic rally and a video interview with his son, the president created awkward images and relived a battle with an incline.
docs.lead_paragraph: When he took the stage Saturday night in Tulsa, Okla., it had been more than three months since President Trump had held one of his treasured campaign rallies. But they say giving a rally speech is like walking down a gently inclined ramp: It’s incredibly treacherous and harrowing, but after what seems like an endless amount of time, you eventually reach bottom.

headline.main: Onscreen, the Trump Campaign Ramps Up, and Down
headline.print_headline: The Battle of the Ramp, From West Point to Tulsa
